column14: @ Uncertainty: IVE method, 2-sigma value (2 x Uncertainty Value reported in *.ft File). @ Good measurement, wade in line with gauge. DWL from primary at arrival. DWL and ECG matched exactly. Amasser in well changing water level at every reading, SRC varying, suspect that amasser is valid, and has a delayed reactino to dropping stage in river. Float and weight in well appear normal. Reset amasser for 10:10, appears to not have reset correctly. Found water level in well to be dropping over time, and matched the drop observed in the logger. Cut on stadia rod in river was dropping at similar rate. Reset logger again for 10:30, after observing stage drop, reset took. Installed OTT as HG at 11:40, swapped Amasser to HG2. DWL at 10:50 confirmed HG2 (amasser) was reading correctly, and HG (OTT) was reading head stage. Reset OTT for 11:55 Mid-section

column14: @ Uncertainty: IVE method, 2-sigma value (2 x Uncertainty Value reported in *.ft File). @ Edited measurement file. Panel at 4.5m was heavily negative flow. Hole was drilled around large rocks in channel. Measurement attempted multiple times. Leaving panel included in measurement created over estimated flow in the shouldering panels, causing them to go above 60% of the total flow each. Multiple panels over 10%, multiple panels with reverse flow. Low and variable SNRs, boundary interference, and spikes at edges. Well appeared good upon arrival, all heat lamps and tape functional, but stage unusually stable. Both intakes were in the open position, upper intake out of water. Closed intakes and flushed at 7:41, re-opened intakes just after 7:42, water level dropped significantly for 7:45, watched water level in well receed. Assumed that lower intake was plugged and purge cleared it. Stage data prior to 7:45 likely invalid, water level continued to drop. External DWL was within 0.003m of the ECG water level. Due to the rapidly changing water level did not immediately reset logger. The logger was reset for 8:10 to the external DWL, assumed that the ECG readings were still fluctuating due to the change in water level inside the well. Mid-section
